</p>
<p>So guess what? To <em>remove</em> that link and delete the row in the join table, we do
the exact opposite: <em>remove</em> the <code>User</code> from the <code>genusScientists</code> property and
save. Doctrine will notice that the <code>User</code> is missing from that collection and
take care of the rest.</p>
<h2 id="setting-up-the-template">Setting up the Template <a class="headerlink" href="removing-items#setting-up-the-template" title="Permalink to this headline"><i class="fa fa-link" aria-hidden="true"></i></a></h2>
<p>Let's start inside the the <code>genus/show.html.twig</code> template. Add a new link for
each user: give some style classes, and a special <code>js-remove-scientist-user</code>
class that we'll use in JavaScript. Add a cute close icon:</p>
